# Technology O/X
> Computers and the internet basics
// Swiq — https://swiq.jiun.dev/set/seed.en.it-tech.tech/

CPU stands for Central Processing Unit. | O | CPU is short for Central Processing Unit, the main processor of a computer.
'www' stands for World Wide Web. | O | www stands for World Wide Web, the system of web pages on the internet.
Email addresses usually contain the '@' symbol. | O | An email address places the '@' symbol between the user name and the domain.
Wi-Fi lets devices connect to the internet without cables. | O | Wi-Fi uses radio signals to connect devices to a network without wires.
1 gigabyte (GB) is larger than 1 megabyte (MB). | O | 1 GB is about 1,000 MB, so it is much larger than 1 MB.
Android and iOS are operating systems for smartphones. | O | Android (Google) and iOS (Apple) are the two most widely used smartphone operating systems.
RAM keeps all its data even after the computer is turned off. | X | RAM is volatile memory; its contents are lost when the power is off.
HTML is an antivirus program. | X | HTML is a markup language used to build web pages, not an antivirus program.
One byte is smaller than one bit. | X | One byte equals eight bits, so a byte is larger than a bit.
iOS is an operating system made by Google. | X | iOS is made by Apple; Google makes Android.
A 'URL' is a type of computer virus. | X | A URL is a web address that points to a page or file, not a virus.
The internet was invented in the year 1500. | X | The internet grew out of networks developed in the 20th century, not in 1500.
